Aerostack Quote-to-Cash (Q2C) Scope — v0.1
0. Purpose and framing
This document scopes the Q2C domain of Aerostack, the enterprise internal work system. It defines the interactions, features, data, and integrations required for Aerostack to run enterprise's quote-to-cash process across all current revenue lines.
Aerostack is the internal system of record. A subset of it may later be repackaged and sold as product. This scope is written so the internal requirements are complete first; product packaging is a derivative concern and is flagged where it affects design choices.
The Q2C problem Aerostack must solve (from practice reality, not assumption):
enterprise sells bundles that mix delivery types in a single customer relationship: assessment → pilot → modernize → manage/scale. A single account can have concurrent VALIDATE (paid discovery), BUILD (fixed-fee/T&M project), and OPERATE (recurring managed services) revenue streams.
Two managed resell channels run in parallel (Graphite via TD Synnex, enterprise via Ingram), with a third layer of enterprise-delivered managed services sitting on top regardless of which party owns the resell relationship.
Revenue splits, referral fees, and AWS funding offsets change by engagement stage and must be computed per-deal for internal accounting and partner reporting.
The investment step-down mechanism (GGTC investment drops at $250K / $500K / $1M Practice MRR) means Aerostack must compute Practice MRR correctly — this is a contract-layer calculation, not a reporting afterthought.
Marketplace offerings (~20–30 across three solution lines) each have their own pricing model, fulfillment pattern, and rev-rec treatment.
Complex periodic and custom terms are normal, not exceptional: "two months free," "5% annual escalator," "billing begins at implementation acceptance," "first-year flat + usage thereafter."
Aerostack must handle all of this without a human serving as the coordination engine.

1. Scope boundaries
In scope for this document:
Quote construction and approval
Contract generation, signature, and activation
Order and fulfillment hand-off (to delivery pods, CSP ops, LaunchLogic ops)
Invoicing, billing, collections
Revenue recognition inputs (Aerostack provides the data; the GL tool does rev-rec)
Partner/channel attribution and tiered referral calculation
AWS funding offset tracking (MAP, EBA, IWA/IWB) against customer invoices
Out of scope for this document (adjacent Aerostack domains):
Lead → qualified opportunity (CRM / CLARIFY stage — feeds into Q2C but lives in Aerostack CRM module)
Delivery pod staffing and timesheet capture (Aerostack Delivery module — upstream of T&M invoicing)
CSP consumption monitoring and anomaly detection (Aerostack One-CT module — feeds usage into Q2C billing)
Rev-rec policy decisions and GL posting (accounting system; Aerostack is the source-of-truth for the inputs)
Assumed layers Aerostack depends on (validated against transcript):
A CRM (HubSpot today; Salesforce-ready path) holds opportunities and account relationships.
A billing execution layer (candidate: Union; alternatives: Orb, Metronome, in-house on Stripe) handles subscription management, metered usage, and invoice generation.
Aerostack sits between CRM and billing as the source of truth for the commercial deal — the structured translation of "what sales sold" into "what billing charges and what delivery fulfills."

