2.2 End-to-end flow — CLARIFY → VALIDATE → BUILD → OPERATE
The flow inherits the four-stage engagement lifecycle from the GGTC partnership model. Aerostack Q2C activates at the transition from CLARIFY → VALIDATE (first paid engagement) and runs continuously through OPERATE.
Stage 1 — CLARIFY → VALIDATE transition (first quote)
Opportunity graduates in CRM (qualified, solution line identified, band-tier estimated).
Seller opens deal in Aerostack, selects solution line (S1/S2/S3) and one or more marketplace offerings from the catalog.
Aerostack pre-fills an engagement-lifecycle template with default VALIDATE scope (e.g., MAP assessment, EBA workshop).
Seller configures scope: user counts, data volumes, AWS funding eligibility flags, partner-of-record selection.
Aerostack runs pricing logic → produces a quote with: assessment fee, net-of-AWS-funding view, anticipated BUILD range, OPERATE recurring estimate.
Approval routing: standard terms auto-approve; non-standard (custom discount, payment terms, bundled free months) route to practice leader.
Contract generated from template → signed in e-sign → Aerostack marks VALIDATE activated.
Stage 2 — VALIDATE execution
Order handed to delivery lead (assessment pod or EBA workshop lead).
Milestones tracked (kickoff, findings, readout). Invoicing triggers per milestone OR on completion, per contract terms.
AWS funding claim submitted in parallel; Aerostack tracks claim status and applies funding offset to customer invoice or partner reimbursement as appropriate.
Outputs of VALIDATE (findings, pilot recommendation) become inputs to a BUILD quote if the customer proceeds — the BUILD quote re-uses account data, so the seller is not re-keying anything.
Stage 3 — BUILD quote and execution
New quote ties to existing account; solution line carries over; offerings may be combined (e.g., one BUILD scope + one OPERATE subscription committed up front).
BUILD pricing supports fixed-fee, T&M, or hybrid. T&M requires timesheet integration for periodic invoicing.
Contract amendments (scope changes, change orders) generate new line items linked to the parent contract — not new contracts — so the customer sees a coherent relationship.
Completion of BUILD triggers automatic activation of the committed OPERATE subscription (LaunchLogic tier, CSP tier, or cost-opt). No re-contracting required if OPERATE was pre-committed.
Stage 4 — OPERATE (recurring, evergreen)
LaunchLogic / CSP / CostOpt runs on subscription terms. Monthly billing with optional metered usage overlay.
CSP consumption data flows from cloud provider → One-CT → Aerostack → billing layer → invoice.
Managed resell margin on cloud consumption is computed at the resell-channel level (TD Synnex vs. Ingram) and attributed to sourcing party for referral.
Tiered referral to GGTC computed on managed services revenue from GGTC-sourced accounts (1% baseline, up to 5% strategic).
Practice MRR is computed continuously for investor reporting and step-down triggers.
2.3 Non-happy-path flows (must be first-class)
Scope change mid-BUILD → change order, re-price, re-approve, amend contract without breaking the parent deal.
Customer pauses OPERATE → subscription suspension, pro-rated credit, clear reactivation path.
AWS funding claim denied → re-invoice customer for the full amount, reconcile with finance.
Partner-of-record change → channel reassignment, margin re-attribution going forward, prior invoices locked.
Custom evergreen term (e.g., "billing starts at implementation acceptance") → Aerostack holds the activation gate, triggers billing on delivery-system signal.
Price protection / grandfathering → catalog version pinned at contract execution; future catalog changes do not touch active contracts.
Multi-entity billing (US entity bills US customer, EU entity bills EU customer from same master agreement) → entity-aware invoicing (see transcript: Union pitched this as a differentiator).
