5.4 Deployment considerations
Per the Union transcript and enterprise's broader GRC posture, Aerostack should be designed for two deployment modes from day one:
enterprise-tenant SaaS (default internal use; potential future multi-tenant product).
Customer-tenant deploy for GRC-sensitive buyers (if Aerostack is repackaged as product).
The core model, APIs, and data schema should not differ between modes. This affects how we pick the billing vendor — white-labelable and tenancy-flexible is a must ([transcript 22:03 — "We're flexible. Yeah. And we'll have those questions. We've got a deployment platform and things like that."]).

6. PC3 as worked example (validation pass)
To validate the model end-to-end, here's how Aerostack PC3 (Channel Command) migrations fit:
Offering catalog entry: "Aerostack PC3 Migration — $3K per unit, S2 solution line, fixed-fee one-time, fulfillment pod type = PC3 migration engine, AWS funding eligible (program attribution variable)."
Quote: A 200-unit pipeline deal becomes 200 line items on one Quote (or a bulk line with unit count), total $600K.
Contract: Fixed-fee schedule with milestone acceptance per batch of units.
Order: Sent to the PC3 migration pod (Akash / Ahmad-owned engineering team per GGTC Eng Team Brief).
Milestones: Per-batch acceptance drives invoicing (e.g., 25-unit batches → 8 invoices over project life).
OPERATE hand-off: Post-migration, partner-of-record relationships feed into managed resell and may trigger follow-on LaunchLogic / CSP engagements — which become new Quotes on the same Account, not new Accounts.
Practice MRR impact: PC3 itself is a one-time BUILD-category revenue stream, so it does NOT count toward Practice MRR. The LaunchLogic/CSP OPERATE subscriptions that follow DO count.
Tiered referral: If GGTC sourced the migrations via a distribution motion, referral attaches to the downstream OPERATE revenue, not the PC3 migration fee (per the partnership model — referral is on managed services revenue specifically).
This worked example exercises every major capability in Sections 3 and 4 and exposes no model gaps at the scoping level.

7. Open questions and follow-ups
These are intentionally called out so they can be closed before v0.2:
Repo verification — github.com/enterpriseio/enterprise-aerostack and github.com/enterpriseio/enterprise-documentation-standards could not be fetched in this session (provenance restriction). Next pass should: (a) confirm Aerostack module naming matches the code, (b) map existing schemas to the entities in Section 4, (c) follow the actual documentation-standards template rather than this inferred structure.
Billing vendor decision — Build vs. buy is live. Union is a strong candidate based on the transcript (multi-entity, multi-currency, B2B-SaaS-built, 8 years battle-tested, API-open, flexible integration). Recommend treating the Q2C spine (this document) as vendor-agnostic and probing Union's engineer on April 29 against Section 3.5, 3.6, 3.7, and 5.2 specifically.
CRM migration timeline — Transcript notes HubSpot cost is scaling 3x this year and the intent is to exit when it hits ~$20K/mo. Aerostack Q2C must not be tightly coupled to HubSpot — design for CRM-agnostic opportunity ingest.
Tax engine path — Avalara / TaxJar covered for US. India tax and future APJ tax are flagged in the transcript as real gaps. Aerostack should support a pluggable tax engine, not a hardcoded one.
E-sign choice — not named. Confirm (DocuSign assumed).
Rev-rec policy — This doc scopes Aerostack as the input side of rev-rec; the actual policy (ASC 606 treatment of bundles, allocation methodology) is an accounting decision that should be documented separately and linked back here.
S4 solution line — Data Readiness & AI Governance was mentioned in an architecture one-pager but not in the GGTC partnership deal. Confirm status and include in catalog if active.
Product packaging decision gates — If Aerostack is repackaged as product later, we need to know which tenancy, which branding surface, and which feature subset. The current doc assumes "internal first, don't preclude product."
Investor view design — The step-down mechanism is operationally critical but deserves its own UX spec; recommend a v0.2 addendum.
Joint-delivery contract model — Contracts where Graphite is resell-party-of-record but enterprise delivers OPERATE need careful multi-party signature and attribution design. Flagged in Section 3.3 but not fully specified.

